  "prompt": "Which is correct, \"best wish\" or \"best wishes\" to you\"?",
  "response": "The correct phrase is **\"best wishes to you.\"**\n\n### Explanation:\n\n- **\"Best wishes\" (plural)** is the standard and widely accepted expression used to convey good thoughts, hopes, or sentiments to someone. It implies multiple good thoughts or desires for someone's well-being.\n\n  - **Example:** *\"Best wishes to you on your new adventure!\"*\n\n- **\"Best wish\" (singular)** is less common and generally not used in standard greetings or farewells. Using the singular form might sound unusual or incomplete in most contexts.\n\n  - **Less Common Usage Example:** While \"best wish\" isn't typically used on its own, it might appear within a larger sentence where \"wish\" is part of a broader expression. However, even in such cases, \"wishes\" remains more natural.\n\n### Additional Common Expressions:\n\n- **\"All the best to you.\"**\n- **\"Wishing you all the best.\"**\n- **\"Best of luck to you.\"**\n\nThese alternatives also effectively convey good intentions and are widely accepted in both written and spoken English.\n\n### Summary:\n\nWhen expressing good intentions or sentiments, **\"best wishes to you\"** is the correct and most commonly used form.",
